{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b1a73700-868a-4b4f-8f45-928f4b613151","content":"Both are **C# 15 breaking changes**:\n\n---\n\n**1. `&&` with `dynamic` operand** — C# 15 now correctly rejects user-defined `&&`/`||` when one operand is `dynamic`. The short-circuit operators require compile-time resolution of `operator true`/`operator false` on the result type, which is impossible when `dynamic` defers binding to runtime.\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `dynamic` or split the short-circuit manually:\n\n```csharp\nvoid Apply(IFilter left, IFilter right)        // preferred: drop dynamic\n{\n    var combined = left && right;\n}\n\n// or, if dynamic is necessary:\nvoid Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)\n{\n    IFilter r = (IFilter)right;\n    var combined = left && r;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `ref readonly` return in lambda — CS0518** — C# 15 changed how the compiler emits metadata for `ref readonly` returns in lambdas. It now requires `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute`, which only ships with the .NET 11 runtime libraries. If your project still targets an older TFM (e.g., `net10.0`), the type is missing and you get CS0518.\n\n**Fix:** Ensure you're targeting `net11.0`:\n\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nOr, if you must target an older framework, polyfill the attribute:\n\n```csharp\nnamespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices\n{\n    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Parameter, Inherited = false)]\n    internal sealed class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"12f4a623-684b-479d-8a83-e352656e353a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both issues.\n\n**Issue 1: `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how `&&` and `||` operators work with `dynamic` operands. Previously, the compiler would allow short-circuit operators (`&&`, `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`, even if the static type of the other operand defined `operator true`/`operator false` on an interface. \n\nIn C# 15, there's a breaking change where `&&` and `||` with `dynamic` operands now require that `operator true`/`operator false` be resolved at compile time on the static type. Since `IFilter` defines these operators as static interface members, and the `right` operand is `dynamic`, the compiler can't resolve the short-circuit evaluation properly at compile time.\n\n\nThe short-circuit operators need `operator true`, `operator false`, and `operator &` all defined, and when one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler's resolution strategy has changed—it no longer allows the compilation to succeed in cases where it previously did.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda issue, the CS0518 error suggests a missing predefined type or member that's required in C# 15, possibly related to how `ref readonly` returns are handled in lambda expressions. In C# 15, the `&&` and `||` operators have a breaking change where they no longer work with `dynamic` operands when user-defined `operator true`/`operator false` are involved, since short-circuit evaluation requires compile-time resolution. For the `ref readonly` lambda issue, the compiler now needs the `RequiresLocationAttribute` type to be available in the target framework, and if it's missing, you get the CS0518 error. The `&&` operator with `dynamic` is a C# 15 breaking change because short-circuit evaluation requires compile-time resolution of `operator true`/`operator false`, which can't happen when `dynamic` is involved. The fix is to cast the `dynamic` value or use the explicit `&` operator instead.\n\nFor `ref readonly` lambdas, C# 15 now requires a specific compiler attribute that may not exist in older target frameworks, causing CS0518. The solution is to target .NET 11.0 or manually define the missing attribute. For the first issue, C# 15 treats `&&` and `||` with `dynamic` operands as a compile-time error now instead of attempting runtime binding, so I'd need to replace that with explicit bitwise operations or remove the dynamic typing altogether. For the second issue, `ref readonly` returns in lambdas now require the compiler to emit specific metadata that depends on `System.Runtime.CompilerServices.RequiresLocationAttribute` being available.\n\nThe fix is to target `net11.0` or later, which includes that attribute, or polyfill it if you're stuck on an older framework version.","outputTokens":2485,"requestId":"680A:24244F:107BCF2:14D65A1:69FFE37E"},"id":"8860a2ef-6408-493d-9023-4f4cdd9e4194","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:47:26.787Z","parentId":"bd2817a0-cebf-4e61-b95a-6623140f86cc"}
